Lab 3: Visualization with ggplot2

This week we introduced how to make more esthetically pleasing plots using ggplot2. For the remainder of the course youll be expected to use ggplot2 any time you create a plot. Many more plotting examples will be presented in class, but lets get more practice now.

Recall this figure from the intro-to-ggplot.Rmd lecture file:

Remake the plot above but

  1. flip the variables so that total is in the x-axis and population is in the y-axis
  2. show the state names instead of the abbreviation
  3. make the points smaller

Solution:

data(murders)
murders %>% ggplot() + 
            geom_point(aes(x=total, y=population/10^6), size = 0.5) + 
            geom_text(aes(x=total, y=population/10^6, label = state))

Grids of plots

Rather than using facet_wrap or facet_grid, there is another option for graphing plots next to each other: the gridExtra package permits us to do that. First create and name all of the plots you wish to show in the same window. Then use the function grid.arrange() and specificy which plots you want to include and how many columns you want to organize them in.

Below is an example using the heights data set. We define p to be a histogram of male heights and p1, p2, and p3 to be the same histogram but with different binwidths i.e.different widths for the rectangles that make up the histogram.

p <- heights %>% filter(sex == "Male") %>% 
                 ggplot(aes(x = height)) 

p1 <- p + geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = "blue", col="black")
p2 <- p + geom_histogram(binwidth = 2, fill = "blue", col="black")
p3 <- p + geom_histogram(binwidth = 3, fill = "blue", col="black")

To print them all side-by-side, we can use the function grid.arrange in the gridExtra package:

library(gridExtra)
grid.arrange(p1,p2,p3, ncol = 3)

Here, ncol specifies how many columns I want to arrange my plot in.

  1. Using the gapminder dataset, filter the data frame so only data from the year 2015 is kept.

Solution

data(gapminder)
gapminder <- gapminder %>% filter(year == "2015")
  1. Create a histogram of fertility, and a second histogram of life expectancy. Then use grid.arrange() to plot the histograms on top of each other in the same window.

Solution

p1 <- gapminder %>% ggplot(aes(x = fertility)) +          
                    geom_histogram(color = "black")

p2 <- gapminder %>% ggplot(aes(x = life_expectancy))  +                            
                    geom_histogram(color = "black")

grid.arrange(p1,p2, ncol = 1)

Vaccines

For homework #2 youll be working with the us_contagious_diseases dataset in the dslabs package. The data were collected, organized and distributed by the Tycho Project. They include weekly reported counts data for seven diseases from 1928 to 2011, from all fifty states. We include the yearly totals in the dslabs package:

library(dslabs)
data("us_contagious_diseases")
  1. Use the us_contagious_disease dataset and dplyr tools to create an object called dat that stores only the Smallpox data, includes a per 10,000 people rate, and removes Alaska and Hawaii since they only became states in the late 1950s. Do not include years in which cases were not reported in 10 or more weeks.

Solution

dat <- us_contagious_diseases %>% 
       filter(!state %in% c("Hawaii", "Alaska") & 
       disease == "Smallpox" & weeks_reporting >= 10) %>%
       mutate(rate = count / population * 10000)
  1. Calculate the US average number of cases of Smallpox per 10,000 people for each year. Do not include years in which cases were not reported.

Solution

avg <- us_contagious_diseases %>%
       filter(disease == "Smallpox") %>% 
       group_by(year) %>%
       summarize(us_rate = sum(count, na.rm=TRUE)/sum(population, na.rm=TRUE)*10000)
  1. Make a the time series plot of the number of cases of Smallpox per 10,000 people for all states and add a line for the US average.

Solution

dat %>% ggplot() + geom_line(aes(year, rate, group = state),  
                             color = "grey50", 
                             show.legend = FALSE, 
                             alpha = 0.2, size = 1) +
                   geom_line(mapping = aes(year, us_rate),
                             data = avg, 
                             size = 1, 
                             color = "black") +
                   scale_y_continuous(trans = "sqrt") +
                   ggtitle("Cases per 10,000 by state") + 
                   xlab("") + 
                   ylab("")

  1. For the state of California, make a time series plot showing rates for all diseases. Include only years with 10 or more weeks reporting. Use a different color for each disease.

Solution

us_contagious_diseases %>% filter(state == "California" & weeks_reporting >= 10) %>%
                           mutate(rate = count/population*10000) %>%
                           ggplot(aes(year, rate, color = disease)) + 
                           geom_line()
